<p>Our compression ratio calculator estimates the value of the CR and the t=
otal engine volume. You may calculate it by multiplying the displacement vo=
lume by the number of cylinders.</p></div></div></div></section><section da=
ta-testid=3D"articleSection-2" data-cwv-id=3D"calculator-article-section" i=
d=3D"static-vs-dynamic-compression-ratio" class=3D"css-qtz96j e1taq3sq0"><h=
2 data-testid=3D"articleSectionHeader-2" class=3D"css-1xbj7gb">Static vs. d=
ynamic compression ratio</h2><div data-testid=3D"articleSectionText" class=
=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><div=
 class=3D"textBlock"><p>Using the compression ratio formulas above, you wil=
l be able to compute the <strong>static compression ratio</strong>. However=
, this number does not perfectly describe reality. Why? It doesn't take int=
o account the closing of the intake valve.</p>
<p>In a combustion engine, the piston moves up and down. When it moves up, =
the volume inside the cylinder is compressed; when it moves down, fresh fue=
l and air enter the chamber through the intake valve. The piston reaches it=
s lowest position (bottom dead center) and starts moving up again. At that =
time, though, the intake valve is not yet closed, so <strong>no compression=
 occurs</strong> =E2=80=93 the air is "pushed out" through the valve. We ca=
n only speak about compression once the valve is completely closed. This is=
 why the dynamic compression ratio (DCR) is dependent on the <strong>intake=
 valve closing</strong> (IVC) point, which is expressed as an angle after t=
he bottom dead center (ABDC). You can discover more in Omni's <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.omnicalculator.com/physics/carnot-efficiency" class=3D"js-link">C=
arnot efficiency calculator</a>.</p>
<p>You can open the dynamic compression ratio section of our calculator to =
calculate the DCR based on the modified stroke length, which in turn is der=
ived from the rod length and the IVC.</p></div></div></div></section><secti=
on data-testid=3D"articleSection-3" data-cwv-id=3D"calculator-article-secti=
on" id=3D"whats-the-best-compression-ratio" class=3D"css-qtz96j e1taq3sq0">=
<h2 data-testid=3D"articleSectionHeader-3" class=3D"css-1xbj7gb">What's the=
 best compression ratio?</h2><div data-testid=3D"articleSectionText" class=
=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><div=
 class=3D"textBlock"><p><strong>The higher the compression ratio, the bette=
r the engine performs</strong>. However, you can't increase the compression=
 ratio to infinity. At some point, the combustion chamber won't have enough=
 space to accommodate the combustion, and <strong>detonation</strong> will =
occur.</p>
<p>The resistance of an engine depends on many factors, but one of the most=
 important is the <strong>fuel octane</strong>. The higher the octane, the =
more compression the fuel is able to resist and the higher the potential co=
mpression ratio.</p>
<p>As we mentioned before, the dynamic compression ratio is the one that ha=
ppens inside the engine. That's why, when we talk about the <strong>best co=
mpression ratio</strong>, we should focus on the DCR and not on the static =
CR. Most conventional engines will have the DCR in the range from 8:1 to 8.=
5:1, which corresponds to 10:1 to 12:1 static CR. However, if you're using =
race fuel, it can get much higher, up to 10:1 DCR and 15:1 static CR.</p></=
div></div></div></section><section data-testid=3D"articleSection-4" data-cw=
v-id=3D"calculator-article-section" id=3D"faqs" class=3D"css-qtz96j e1taq3s=
q0"><h2 data-testid=3D"articleSectionHeader-4" class=3D"css-1xbj7gb">FAQs</=
h2><div data-testid=3D"articleSectionText" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><=
h3 data-testid=3D"How can I calculate compression ratio of a petrol engine?=
" class=3D"css-1ugw61y">How can I calculate compression ratio of a petrol e=
ngine?</h3><div data-testid=3D"How can I calculate compression ratio of a p=
etrol engine?-answer" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0=
 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><div class=3D"textBlock"><p>To calculate the compres=
sion ratio, you may use the formula:</p>
<p><strong>CR =3D (V<sub>d</sub> + V<sub>c</sub>) / V<sub>c</sub></strong><=
/p>
<p>So, let's suppose you are using the values of your petrol engine and fol=
low the steps below.</p>
<ol>
<li>Suppose the displacement volume(V<sub>d</sub>) is <code>52 cc</code>;</=
li>
<li>The compressed volume (V<sub>c</sub>) is <code>8 cc</code>;</li>
<li>Sum the values, and the result is <code>60</code>;</li>
<li>Now divide 60 by 8 (V<sub>c</sub>); and</li>
<li>The result is a compression ratio of <code>7.5:1</code>.</li>
</ol></div></div></div><h3 data-testid=3D"What is a good compression ratio?=
" class=3D"css-1ugw61y">What is a good compression ratio?</h3><div data-tes=
tid=3D"What is a good compression ratio?-answer" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3=
sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><div class=3D"textBlock">=
<p>A <strong>high compression ratio is good</strong> as it is directly prop=
ortional to the engine's performance. But that doesn't imply you should tak=
e it to infinity.</p>
<p>Remember, if you want the best compression ratio, then your focus should=
 be the dynamic compression ratio(DCR) instead of static. For <strong>tradi=
tional engines, the DCR ranges between 8:1 to 8.5:1</strong>. And if you're=
 using race fuel, expect a much higher ratio up to 10:1 DSR.</p></div></div=
></div><h3 data-testid=3D"Are static and dynamic compression ratio the same=
?" class=3D"css-1ugw61y">Are static and dynamic compression ratio the same?=
</h3><div data-testid=3D"Are static and dynamic compression ratio the same?=
-answer" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e=
1m4c3o81"><div class=3D"textBlock"><p><strong>No, they are different from e=
ach other.</strong></p>
<p>The <strong>static compression ratio</strong> doesn't take into account =
the closing of the intake valve, which impacts the practicality of the resu=
lts.</p>
<p>The <strong>dynamic compression ratio(DRC)</strong>, on the other hand, =
gives the actual cylinder pressure because it changes dynamically and hence=
 provides information about how the engine will perform.</p></div></div></d=
iv><h3 data-testid=3D"What happens if compression ratio is too high?" class=
=3D"css-1ugw61y">What happens if compression ratio is too high?</h3><div da=
ta-testid=3D"What happens if compression ratio is too high?-answer" class=
=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><div=
 class=3D"textBlock"><p>We know a high compression ratio is good, but we do=
n't want it too high. As <strong>it causes the engine to knock, which is th=
e same as detonation</strong>. This can, in turn, lead to <strong>engine da=
mage and reduced efficiency</strong>.</p></div></div></div></div></section>=
